The Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Z. Jiang¶

Investigation Overview¶

This is a finanacial dataset related to the loan, lenders, borrowers, interest rates, monthly payments, incomes, etc. This dataset is from the Propsper Marketplace Inc., a San Francisco California based company specializing in loan at low interest rates to the borrowers. The variables included the borrower's location, financial, credit records, the evaluation measurement made by the Prosper platform, and the investors' information. In the next few sections, I will clean up the data and explore the loan data through applying univariate, bivariate, and multivariate graphs and summaries. Specifically, I explored the dataset to address the concerns listed below.

  1. What are the characteristics of the borrowers on the Prosper platform.
  2. What are the factors that play critical roles in determining the borrower rate.
  3. How the Prosper platform evaluate and manage the risk for the investors.
  4. The pattern of the investors' preference in choosing the borrowers.

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables. Each loan record contains the loan amount, borrower rate (interest rate), current loan status, borrower's employment status, borrower income, and borrower credit history.

The data analysis below is based on my personal interests listed above, therefore I pre-selected the data accordingly.

This ananlysis is consisted by three major sections: Univariate Section, Bivariate Section, and Multivariate Section. I will analyze one variate

Who borrows money on Prosper and the reasons¶

The chart clearly shows most borrowers on Prosper live in California, followed by Texas, New York, and Florida. Since the Prosper is located in California, it is not surprising that the people live in California using the Prosper plaform. The other interesting finding from this chart is in general, theere are more borrowers from the coast line states than the inner states.

The top five states of the borrowers on Prosper are California, Texas, New York, Florida, and Illinois.

Where the large sum of money go?¶

Since most of the money went to the top five states as shown above, I focused on the top five states and further investigated where the large amount of loan money went.

  • The plot shows five significant peaks of the original amount of the loan: 4k, 10k, 15k, 20k, and 25k.
  • The 4k peak is very peculiar compare to the rest four peaks because the loan amount is much smaller and unlike the rest major peaks, 4k falls out of the 5k arithmeci sequence the rest four peaks follows.
  • So, why so many borrowers borrow 4k on Prosper?

Before I dive into the dataset, let's explore the another aspect of the borrower's background information.

What the borrowers do for a living¶

  • Most borrowers on Prosper are Professional, Computer Programmer, Executive, Teacher, Aministrative Assistant, and Analyst. Note: The borrowers who self-identified as 'Other' in the occupation column have been excluded from the this analysis.
  • The top five occupation workers are usually regarded as well educated, creditworthy, and have relatively high income.
  • The large number of executives also borrow money from the Prosper platform is very surprising.

Other important features of the borrowers on Prosper¶

  • The first plot shows on average, the borrower has worked three years by the moment he/she apply for the loan.
  • The second plot shows the averagae monthly income of the borrower is around USD5.6k.
  • The third plot shows most of the borrowers have at least one Prosper loan by the time they posted the listings. Most of the borrowers are not first time user of Prosper system.
  • Most borrowers choose three years loan followed by five years loan. Very few borrowers choose the short term one year or less than one year loan.

Data Wrangling before further exploration¶

Because the ProsperRating records did not exist prior to July 2009, it shows as missing data in the earlier records. Prior to 2009, the CreditGrade was used as the evaluation system by Prosper. Since we have more ProsperRating over CrediGrade records, the rows with the CrediGrade records will be excluded from this analysis. The additional rows with the conditions below will also be exclude.

  • The borrower's income information is missing
  • The borrower rate is above 0.35
  • Missing employment status information
  • Credit socre lower than 400
In [12]:

Summary:¶

  • Prosper rating is highly correlated with the borrower rate. An improving prosper rating(from HR to AA means the risk is from high to low) indicates a decreasing borrower rate.
  • Higher income makes the borrower rate distribution peak shift towards the left.
  • Most borrowers are employed.
  • Being a house owner does help to lower the borrower rate.

The odd 4k peak was caused by borrowers with bad Prosper ratings¶

  • The plot shows the borrower has higher prosper rating scales D, E, and HR (high risk) obtain less amount of loan money. The average amount of the loan money for E and HR borrowers is around 4k.
  • Since the borrower with high prosper rating scale indicate a high risk, it is reasonable that these borrowers (D, E, HR) will have more difficulties to borrow larger loan amounts on the Prosper platform

The highly aggregated 4k loan amount for the E and HR borrowers explained the 4k peak in the first loan amount distribution histogram chart ealier.

In [26]:
# apply cuberoot transformation
def qrt_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """transformation helper function"""
    if not inverse:
        return x ** (1/4)
    else:
        return x ** 4
    
bin_edges = np.arange(0, qrt_trans(loan['DebtToIncomeRatio'].max())+0.06, 0.06);
plt.hist(loan['DebtToIncomeRatio'].apply(qrt_trans), bins = bin_edges);
tick_locs = np.arange(0, qrt_trans(loan['DebtToIncomeRatio'].max())+0.6, 0.6);
plt.xticks(tick_locs, qrt_trans(tick_locs, inverse = True).astype(int));

  • The plot shows at the same borrower rate (like 0.2, 0.25), the estimated yield is below zero for HR (high risk borrower) but positive for AA, A and B (low risk borrowers).

Now we know that the Prosper rating can reflect borrower's debt pressure and predict borrower's risk. But the loan amount is what the borrower cares most and we need to know whether the investors can take advantages of the Prosper system to reduce their risk and maximize their profits.¶

Lets first take a look at the two heat maps of loan amount vs. borrower rate and loan amount vs. investor distribution¶

The heat maps of borrower rate vs. loan amount; loan amount vs. investors¶

  • The loan amount tend to fall on 4k, 10k, 15k, 20k, and 25k these five peaks.
  • On each specific loan amount peak, the borrower rate has a wide spread.
  • Specifically, at the 4k peak, more counts is obseved at higher borrower rate range (0.25 to 0.32).
  • On 10k, 15k, 20k, and 25k loan amount peaks, the borrower rate mainly aggregate from 0.1 to 0.25.

  • At higher loan amount 20k and 25k, the borrower rate shift towards the left compare to the lower loan amount 10k and 4k.

  • Borrowers received 10k, 15k loan amount attracted more investors on average.

# apply cuberoot transformation
def sqrt_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """transformation helper function"""
    if not inverse:
        return x ** (1/2)
    else:
        return x ** 2
    
bin_edges = np.arange(0, sqrt_trans(loan['Investors'].max())+3.4, 3.4);
plt.hist(loan['Investors'].apply(sqrt_trans), bins = bin_edges);
tick_locs = np.arange(0, sqrt_trans(loan['Investors'].max())+3.4, 3.4);
plt.xticks(tick_locs, sqrt_trans(tick_locs, inverse = True).astype(int));

def mean_poly(x, y, bins = bin_edges, **kwargs):
    """Custom adapted line plot code."""
    # set bin edges if non or int specified
    if type(bins) == int:
        bins = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), bins+1)
    bin_centers = (bin_edges[1:] + bin_edges[:-1]) / 2
    
    # compute counts
    data_bins = pd.cut(x, bins, right = False,
                       include_lowest = True)
    means = y.groupby(data_bins).mean()
    
    # create plot
    plt.errorbar(x = bin_centers, y = means, **kwargs)

bin_edges = np.arange(999, loan['LoanOriginalAmount'].max()+1000, 1000)
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = loan, hue = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', height = 5)
g.map(mean_poly, 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'Investors', bins = bin_edges)
g.set_ylabels('mean(Investors)')
plt.legend(['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR'], title = 'ProsperRatings',
           loc = 6, bbox_to_anchor = (1.0, 0.5))
plt.title('Average Investor Number vs. Loan Amount sorted by Prosper Rating')

Final Summary¶

  • The Prosper rating system can reflect the borrowers' debt pressure and designate different borrower rate according to the borrower base on his/her financial records.
  • The Prosper rating system shows the same trend of the borrower's debt pressure as the income range does.
  • Most investors prefer the low risk ,low borrower rate loan to invest.
  • Borrowers with high monthly income enabled them to borrow higher loan amounts.
